What is the inverse of the matrix $$A = \left( {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right)$$ ?

en.explanation:
We have,<br><br>$$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\left| A \right| = 1[{\cos ^2}\theta  - ( - {\sin ^2}\theta )] = 1 \ne 0$$<br><br>$${C_{11}} = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| = \cos \theta $$<br><br>$${C_{12}} =  - \left| {\matrix{
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| = \sin \theta $$<br><br>$${C_{13}} = \left| {\matrix{
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$${C_{21}} =  - \left| {\matrix{
   {\sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| =  - \sin \theta $$<br><br>$${C_{22}} = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| = \cos \theta $$<br><br>$${C_{23}} =  - \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta }  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$${C_{31}} = \left| {\matrix{
   {\sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$${C_{32}} =  - \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$${C_{33}} = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta }  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 

 } } \right| = {\cos ^2}\theta  + {\sin ^2}\theta  = 1$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ adj $$A = {\left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; {\sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]^T}$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $${A^{ - 1}} = {1 \over {\left| A \right|}}$$<br><br>$${A^{ - 1}} = {1 \over 1}\left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$

