If $$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 7  \cr 
   1 &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right]$$, then what is $$A + 3{A^{ - 1}}$$ equal to?<br><br>where, I is the identity matrix of order 2.

en.explanation:
We have, $$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 7  \cr 
   1 &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$\left| A \right| = 10 - 7 = 3$$<br><br>Now, $${A^{ - 1}} = {1 \over {\left| A \right|}}$$ adj (A)<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $${A^{ - 1}} = {1 \over 3}{\left[ {\matrix{
   5 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   { - 7} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right]^T} = {1 \over 3}\left[ {\matrix{
   5 &amp; { - 7}  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$A + 3{A^{ - 1}} = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 7  \cr 
   1 &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right] + 3 \times {1 \over 3}\left[ {\matrix{
   5 &amp; { - 7}  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   7 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 7  \cr 

 } } \right] = 7\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right] = 7I$$

